\begin{exercise}{A}{Algebraic properties}{0000}
\begin{exerciseStatement}

\begin{enumerate}[(a)]
\item 

 Let a set \(S\) have binary operations \(+\) and \(\cdot\) defined. Explain the requirements for \(S\) to be a group (with operation \(+\)), ring, or field. 


\item 

 One of the below Cayley tables does not define a group. Give an example illustrating how it satisfies or fails each of the requirements for a group. 

\[
                      \hspace{1em}
                      \begin{array}{c|cccccc}
\circ & a&b&c&d&f&g\\\hline 
a & b & a & c & f & d & g \\ 
b & a & b & c & d & f & g \\ 
c & c & c & c & g & g & g \\ 
d & f & d & g & f & d & g \\ 
f & d & f & g & d & f & g \\ 
g & g & g & g & g & g & g
\end{array}
                      \hspace{1em}
                      \begin{array}{c|cccccc}
\cdot & 2&4&6&8&10&12\\\hline 
2 & 12 & 10 & 8 & 6 & 4 & 2 \\ 
4 & 8 & 12 & 10 & 2 & 6 & 4 \\ 
6 & 10 & 8 & 12 & 4 & 2 & 6 \\ 
8 & 4 & 6 & 2 & 10 & 12 & 8 \\ 
10 & 6 & 2 & 4 & 12 & 8 & 10 \\ 
12 & 2 & 4 & 6 & 8 & 10 & 12
\end{array}
                  \hspace{1em}
              \]
\item 

 Use results from \verb|https://books.aimath.org/aata/section-mod-n-sym.html| to explain why \(\mathbb Z_{11}\) is a field, but \(\mathbb Z_{14}\) is only a ring. 


\end{enumerate}

    \end{exerciseStatement}
\begin{exerciseAnswer}

